### HYMN LXVII

#### A charm for the destruction and plunder of enemies

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_0606701">1</span></span>Indra and
Pūshan have gone forth along the ways on every side.  
  To-day those hosts of enemies must flee bewildered far away.  
<span class="margnote"><span id="an_0606702">2</span></span>Ye foes,
come hitherward dismayed like serpents when their  
   heads are gone.  
  Let Indra slay each bravest one of you whom Agni hath con-  
   fused.  
<span class="margnote"><span id="an_0606703">3</span></span>Gird thou a
bullock's hide on these, make those as timid as the  
   deer.  
  Let the foe flee away, and let his kine come hither-ward to us.

